It also has some doctors and engineers. Mr Arara told the Nation that some of their members work abroad and promptly send in their contributions. They are required to contribute Sh50 per month.  

Notably, the majority of OWA members do not have any form of health insurance scheme, not even the National Hospital Insurance Fund (NHIF) where one can remit a minimum of Sh500 per month.  

Asked whether OWA has a plan to ensure members have a health insurance plan, as this would reduce deaths of those suffering from treatable illnesses, Mr Arara said: 

"That is not why OWA came into being. But if members were to make such proposals then we can consider. Whatever we subscribe per funeral is less than a dollar but insurance would demand more. That will make OWA expensive for our poor people." 

The death of a member or any child from five years attracts Sh50 per head. This would mean that with all members contributing, OWA has the potential to raise Sh100,000 per funeral. 

The amount is enough to take care of mortuary bills, hearse, tents and chairs, as well as catering for the usual razzmatazz that often characterises funerals in the Luo community. 

OWA has no bank account because funds are contributed during burials and the whole amount committed to that particular funeral. The amount is also spent on meals to entertain mourners. 



