Members also contribute half a kilogramme of maize grain. Currently, OWA has purchased tents and no longer needs to hire during funerals. This has helped the group save on costs. 

If a couple are both members of OWA, each one of them gets to contribute independently. 

Just like a person may have a robust health cover but does not fall sick to ''enjoy'' his or her health insurance, OWA has members who have been contributing for so long but have not died or lost a loved one to use their ''death investment''. 

But no one is giving up. The group’s membership has been growing. In fact, according to the chairperson, today, OWA members have crossed the borders of Kabondo Kasipul Constituency into the neighbouring Kanyango clan of Kasipul Constituency. 

Apart from OWA, there is another group known as ''Bury Yourself'' or Kojwach Moyie. 

Less expensive  

The group is based in the same ward (Kojwach in Kabondo Kasipul constituency). It has members in their thousands and is chaired by Mr Paul Aroko. 

According to Kojwach East Chief James Oindi, the 'Ikri Kendi' organisations in his area have achieved their mission. 

"Funerals have become less expensive. The only thing that your organisation needs to start thinking about is how to enrol members into a health insurance scheme (NHIF). The majority are poor and end up dying of treatable illness due to lack of money to foot hospital bills,” said the administrator. 



